<h1 id="begin">Begin!</h1>

<p>First thing we need to do is start with a block of wood. A nice piece of Sapele will do it. I measured and found that a 1‚Äù knob will fit nicely and be quite large in context.</p>

<p><a href="/assets/Knob/start.jpg"><img src="/assets/Knob/Thumbnails/start.jpg" alt="Start Your Engines!" /></a></p>

<h1 id="turn">Turn</h1>

<p>Now I chuck it up in the lathe to get the profile I want.</p>

<p><a href="/assets/Knob/turn.jpg"><img src="/assets/Knob/Thumbnails/turn.jpg" alt="Now it's round" /></a></p>

<h1 id="drill">Drill</h1>

<p>There needs to be a center hole for this D-shaped knob shaft to go. I toss my drill chuck in the lathe tailstock and get going.</p>

<p><a href="/assets/Knob/drill.jpg"><img src="/assets/Knob/Thumbnails/drill.jpg" alt="Drill the hole" /></a></p>

<p><a href="/assets/Knob/drillmore.jpg"><img src="/assets/Knob/Thumbnails/drillmore.jpg" alt="This time with the lathe on!" /></a></p>

<h1 id="its-almost-a-knob">It‚Äôs almost a knob!</h1>

<p>Get that nasty square part off‚Ä¶</p>

<p><a href="/assets/Knob/cut.jpg"><img src="/assets/Knob/Thumbnails/cut.jpg" alt="Cut off the square" /></a></p>

<p><a href="/assets/Knob/cutdone.jpg"><img src="/assets/Knob/Thumbnails/cutdone.jpg" alt="Now it's a knob!" /></a></p>

<h1 id="give-it-the-d-part-1">Give it the D, part 1</h1>

<p>First step to making the D hole is to cut a little sliver of wood. In this case it‚Äôs exactly 1mm thick.</p>

<p><a href="/assets/Knob/sliver.jpg"><img src="/assets/Knob/Thumbnails/sliver.jpg" alt="A scrap to a sliver" /></a></p>

<p>Now it needs to be trimmed to the correct width with a sharp chisel. Note that you need to go WITH the grain. If you go against it, then it will split in a way you don‚Äôt want. <em>Pay attention to the grain!</em></p>

<p><a href="/assets/Knob/slice.jpg"><img src="/assets/Knob/Thumbnails/slice.jpg" alt="Slice it down" /></a></p>

<p>Now the back of the slice needs to be rounded so it fits nicely in the hole.</p>

<p><a href="/assets/Knob/roundslice.jpg"><img src="/assets/Knob/Thumbnails/roundslice.jpg" alt="Round it up.. up I guess? Last thing was down, so this must be up" /></a></p>

<h1 id="give-it-the-d-part-2">Give it the D, part 2</h1>

<p>Cover the slice in some medium viscocity CA, insert and then spray with some accelerator.</p>

<p><a href="/assets/Knob/putslice.jpg"><img src="/assets/Knob/Thumbnails/putslice.jpg" alt="Makin' the D" /></a></p>

<p>Trim it down to look nice</p>

<p><a href="/assets/Knob/trimslice.jpg"><img src="/assets/Knob/Thumbnails/trimslice.jpg" alt="Make it pretty" /></a></p>

<h1 id="some-indication">Some Indication</h1>

<p>A centerfinder is used to line up the ‚Äòindication point‚Äô on the face. The flat face of the D shaft points perpendicular to the indication mark.</p>

<p><a href="/assets/Knob/center.jpg"><img src="/assets/Knob/Thumbnails/center.jpg" alt="Center the indicator" /></a></p>

<p>I then took a V chisel and cut the indication mark on the face.</p>

<p><a href="/assets/Knob/ready.jpg"><img src="/assets/Knob/Thumbnails/ready.jpg" alt="Ready for Finish" /></a></p>

<h1 id="finish">Finish</h1>

<p>CA as finish! The pen turner‚Äôs favorite thing. I like to apply it with <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Kimberly-Clark-Kimtech-Kimwipes-Delicate-Disposable/dp/B00RORBXA8/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1460401922&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=kimwipes">Kimwipes</a>. These things are my favorite finish application product now.</p>

<p><a href="/assets/Knob/cathin.jpg"><img src="/assets/Knob/Thumbnails/cathin.jpg" alt="Yeah, I use this stuff. It works quite well and it's quick." /></a></p>

<h1 id="finished">Finished</h1>

<p>Only took about 30 minutes. It will probably save me that much time fumbling around in just a few days.</p>

<p><a href="/assets/Knob/done.jpg"><img src="/assets/Knob/Thumbnails/done.jpg" alt="That's it!. Please look at the plastic and the bubbles. FEEL IT. FEEEEELLLLL IIIITTTTTTT" /></a></p>

<p>Yes, I keep the plastic on all my stuff. <em>Deal with it.</em></p>

